To call the CanceledDelegate when the right mouse button is pressed to cancel targeting in UE5 GAS, you should override the StartTargeting function and bind the CanceledDelegate to a new function, which you will call when the right mouse button is pressed. Here's how you can do this:

1. In your AGameplayAbilityTargetActor_GroundTrace header file (.h), declare a UFUNCTION() to handle the right mouse button press event, like this:

```cpp
UFUNCTION()
void OnRightMouseButtonPressed();
```

2. In your AGameplayAbilityTargetActor_GroundTrace source file (.cpp), override the StartTargeting() function like this:

```cpp
void AGameplayAbilityTargetActor_GroundTrace::StartTargeting(UGameplayAbility* Ability)
{
    Super::StartTargeting(Ability);

    // Get the PlayerController
    APlayerController* PlayerController = MasterPC.Get();

    if (PlayerController)
    {
        // Bind the OnRightMouseButtonPressed event to input
        PlayerController->InputComponent->BindAction("RightMouseButton", IE_Pressed, this, &AGameplayAbilityTargetActor_GroundTrace::OnRightMouseButtonPressed);
    }
}
```

3. Implement the OnRightMouseButtonPressed function like this:

```cpp
void AGameplayAbilityTargetActor_GroundTrace::OnRightMouseButtonPressed()
{
    // Call the CancelTargeting function
    CancelTargeting();

    // Unbind the OnRightMouseButtonPressed event
    APlayerController* PlayerController = MasterPC.Get();
    if (PlayerController && PlayerController->InputComponent)
    {
        PlayerController->InputComponent->RemoveActionBinding("RightMouseButton", IE_Pressed);
    }
}
```

4. If you haven't already, create an input action RightMouseButton in your project's input settings by following these steps:

- Open Edit -> Project Settings
- Under Engine settings, find and click on the "Input" section
- Add a new Action Mapping with the name "RightMouseButton"
- Assign the Right Mouse Button as the key mapped to the action

Now, when you press the right mouse button, the CanceledDelegate should be called to cancel targeting in your AGameplayAbilityTargetActor_GroundTrace class.

To increase the health based on the healing attribute in PostGameplayEffectExecute, you need to do the following:

1. In your AttributeSet class header file (.h), make sure you have the FGameplayAttributeData properties for health and healing:

```cpp
UPROPERTY(BlueprintReadOnly, Category = "Attributes", ReplicatedUsing = OnRep_Health)
FGameplayAttributeData Health;
UFUNCTION()
void OnRep_Health();
UPROPERTY(BlueprintReadOnly, Category = "Attributes")
FGameplayAttributeData Healing;
```

2. Add a static FGameplayAttribute structure for each FGameplayAttributeData in the same header file:

```cpp
static FGameplayAttribute HealthAttribute();
static FGameplayAttribute HealingAttribute();
```

3. Implement these FGameplayAttribute functions in your AttributeSet source file (.cpp):

```cpp
FGameplayAttribute UYourAttributeSet::HealthAttribute()
{
    static UProperty* Property = FindFieldChecked<UProperty>(UYourAttributeSet::StaticClass(), GET_MEMBER_NAME_CHECKED(UYourAttributeSet, Health));
    return FGameplayAttribute(Property);
}

FGameplayAttribute UYourAttributeSet::HealingAttribute()
{
    static UProperty* Property = FindFieldChecked<UProperty>(UYourAttributeSet::StaticClass(), GET_MEMBER_NAME_CHECKED(UYourAttributeSet, Healing));
    return FGameplayAttribute(Property);
}
```

4. Override PostGameplayEffectExecute() in your AttributeSet class header file:

```cpp
virtual void PostGameplayEffectExecute(const struct FGameplayEffectModCallbackData& Data) override;
```

5. Implement PostGameplayEffectExecute() in your AttributeSet class source file:

```cpp
void UYourAttributeSet::PostGameplayEffectExecute(const FGameplayEffectModCallbackData& Data)
{
    Super::PostGameplayEffectExecute(Data);

    // Get the target Attribute that has been modified
    FGameplayAttribute ModifiedAttribute = Data.EvaluatedData.Attribute;

    // Compare it to the HealingAttribute
    if (ModifiedAttribute == HealingAttribute())
    {
        // Compute the new Health value
        float NewHealth = GetHealth() + GetHealing();

        // Clamp Health according to your rules (e.g., max health)
        float MaxHealth = GetMaxHealth(); // Implement GetMaxHealth() based on your logic
        NewHealth = FMath::Clamp(NewHealth, 0.0f, MaxHealth);

        // Set the new Health value
        SetHealth(NewHealth);
    }
}
```

6. Make sure that AttributeSet replication is enabled by setting "bReplicateMoves" flag to true in your AbilitySystemComponent.

Now, when you apply a GameplayEffect that modifies the healing attribute, the PostGameplayEffectExecute function will be called, and it will increase the health based on the healing attribute.

To use FText::Format in Unreal Engine 5, you need to provide a format pattern and substitutions for placeholders in the pattern. The pattern should include placeholders in curly braces "{}" with identifier names or indices inside.

Here's an example:

1. First, add the necessary include headers in your source file:

```cpp
#include "Internationalization/Text.h"
#include "Internationalization/TextFormat.h"
```

2. Then, use FText::Format to create a formatted FText object:

```cpp
FText PlayerName = FText::FromString(TEXT("PlayerOne"));
int32 Score = 1000;

FText FormatPattern = FText::FromString(TEXT("{Player} scored {Score} points!"));
FText FormattedText = FText::Format(FormatPattern, FFormatOrderedArguments{PlayerName, Score});
```

In this example, we create a format pattern "{Player} scored {Score} points!" and substitute the "{Player}" placeholder with PlayerName (PlayerOne), and the "{Score}" placeholder with the Score variable (1000). The resulting FormattedText will be "PlayerOne scored 1000 points!".

You can also use named arguments with FFormatNamedArguments in FText::Format.

```cpp
FText PlayerName = FText::FromString(TEXT("PlayerOne"));
int32 Score = 1000;

FText FormatPattern = FText::FromString(TEXT("{Player} scored {Score} points!"));
FFormatNamedArguments NamedArguments;
NamedArguments.Add(TEXT("Player"), PlayerName);
NamedArguments.Add(TEXT("Score"), FText::AsNumber(Score));

FText FormattedText = FText::Format(FormatPattern, NamedArguments);
```

In this example, we achieve the same result as before but with named arguments. The format pattern is the same, and we create an FFormatNamedArguments object and add the values for the "Player" and "Score" arguments. Then, we call FText::Format with the FormatPattern and NamedArguments to get the formatted text.

In Unreal Engine 5, you typically don't destroy UWidgets directly. Instead, you remove them from the viewport or their parent widget and the garbage collector eventually cleans them up. Here's how to remove a UWidget from the viewport or parent widget:

1. If you have a reference to a UUserWidget (which is a UObject derived class):

```cpp
UUserWidget* MyWidget = /* assuming you have the pointer to your widget */;
```

2. To remove the widget from the viewport, you can use the RemoveFromViewport() function:

```cpp
if (MyWidget && MyWidget->IsInViewport())
{
    MyWidget->RemoveFromViewport();
}
```

3. If the widget you want to remove is not a UUserWidget but a UWidget (e.g., UTextBlock, UImage, etc.) and it is part of another UUserWidget, you can detach it from its parent using the RemoveFromParent() function:

```cpp
UWidget* MyInnerWidget = /* assuming you have the pointer to your widget */;
if (MyInnerWidget)
{
    MyInnerWidget->RemoveFromParent();
}
```

Remember that the garbage collector in Unreal Engine will handle the actual destruction of UWidgets when they are no longer being used or referenced. However, if you want to ensure that the garbage collector cleans them up sooner, you can set the UPROPERTY() of your widget pointers to Transient, like this:

```cpp
UPROPERTY(Transient)
UUserWidget* MyWidget;

UPROPERTY(Transient)
UWidget* MyInnerWidget;
```

This tells the engine not to save the reference between gameplay sessions, making it more likely that the garbage collector will clean it up sooner.

To display some text to the user when targeting using AGameplayAbilityTargetActor_GroundTrace in UE5, you can create a widget that will be displayed on the user's screen during targeting. You will need to create a UUserWidget class, instantiate it when the AGameplayAbilityTargetActor_GroundTrace starts targeting, and remove it when targeting ends (i.e., on confirm or cancel).

Here's a step-by-step guide on how to achieve this:

1. Create a new UUserWidget Blueprint class or a C++ class in your project. This will be the widget that displays the text to the user during targeting. You can name it "TargetTextWidget" or something similar. Design your widget as desired in the UMG editor.

2. In your AGameplayAbilityTargetActor_GroundTrace header file (.h), add a UPROPERTY to store a reference to the widget:

```cpp
UPROPERTY(BlueprintReadWrite, EditAnywhere, Category = "Target Actor")
TSubclassOf<UUserWidget> TargetTextWidgetClass;
```

3. Add a private variable to store the instantiated widget:

```cpp
UPROPERTY(Transient)
UUserWidget* TargetTextWidgetInstance;
```

4. Override the `BeginPlay()` function and call Super:

```cpp
virtual void BeginPlay() override;
```

5. In your AGameplayAbilityTargetActor_GroundTrace source file (.cpp), include the necessary headers:

```cpp
#include "Blueprint/UserWidget.h"
```

6. Implement the BeginPlay function to spawn the widget:

```cpp
void AGameplayAbilityTargetActor_GroundTrace::BeginPlay()
{
    Super::BeginPlay();

    if (IsValid(TargetTextWidgetClass))
    {
        APlayerController* PlayerController = MasterPC.Get();

        if (PlayerController && PlayerController->GetLocalPlayer())
        {
            TargetTextWidgetInstance = CreateWidget<UUserWidget>(PlayerController->GetLocalPlayer(), TargetTextWidgetClass);

            if (TargetTextWidgetInstance)
            {
                TargetTextWidgetInstance->AddToViewport();
            }
        }
    }
}
```

7. In the `OnRightMouseButtonPressed()` and `ConfirmTargeting()` functions, remove the widget from the viewport when targeting is canceled or confirmed:

```cpp
if (TargetTextWidgetInstance && TargetTextWidgetInstance->IsInViewport())
{
    TargetTextWidgetInstance->RemoveFromViewport();
}
```

This way, when you start targeting using the AGameplayAbilityTargetActor_GroundTrace, the TargetTextWidget will be displayed on the user's screen. The text will be removed when targeting is either confirmed or canceled. Remember to set the TargetTextWidgetClass in the Blueprint defaults or constructor of your target actor class.

To use CreateWidget with StaticClass() in Unreal Engine 5, you need to have a UClass pointer to the desired widget class. Instead of using the StaticClass() of your widget class directly in the CreateWidget function, you should hold the class reference in a variable, and then pass that variable to CreateWidget. Here's an example:

1. Include the necessary headers:

```cpp
#include "Blueprint/UserWidget.h"
#include "YourUserWidgetClass.h" // Replace this with the header file for your widget class
```

2. In the class where you want to create the widget, declare a UPROPERTY to hold the UClass pointer of your widget class:

```cpp
UPROPERTY(EditDefaultsOnly, BlueprintReadOnly, Category = "UI")
TSubclassOf<UUserWidget> UserWidgetClass;
```

3. Set the widget class in the constructor of your class (e.g., your custom actor or character class) using StaticClass():

```cpp
YourCustomClass::YourCustomClass()
{
    // ...
    UserWidgetClass = UYourUserWidgetClass::StaticClass(); // Replace UYourUserWidgetClass with the actual name of your widget class
}
```

4. When you want to create the widget, use the CreateWidget function with the UClass pointer:

```cpp
UUserWidget* CreatedWidget = CreateWidget<UUserWidget>(GetWorld(), UserWidgetClass);
if (CreatedWidget)
{
    CreatedWidget->AddToViewport();
}
```

Reminder: The UClass reference you set in your constructor must be valid at the point where you attempt to create the widget. If the reference is not set or invalid, CreateWidget will fail and return a nullptr. Ensure you are using the correct UObject, GetWorld() or a valid player context, and verify that the UserWidgetClass property holds a valid UClass reference of your widget class.

Yes, you can use BindWidget with CreateWidget in Unreal Engine 5. To use BindWidget, you will be working with a C++-based UUserWidget instead of a Blueprint-based one. Here's an example of how to do this:

1. Create a C++ class derived from UUserWidget, let's call it UMyUserWidget:

```cpp
// MyUserWidget.h
#pragma once

#include "CoreMinimal.h"
#include "Blueprint/UserWidget.h"
#include "TextBlock.h"
#include "MyUserWidget.generated.h"

UCLASS()
class YOURPROJECT_API UMyUserWidget : public UUserWidget
{
    GENERATED_BODY()

public:

    UPROPERTY(BlueprintReadOnly, Category = "Text", meta = (BindWidget))
    UTextBlock* TextBlockWidget;
};
```

2. In the class where you want to use this widget, include the headers for the custom widget class and ensure the UserWidgetClass references UMyUserWidget instead of UUserWidget:

```cpp
// Include the header for your custom widget class
#include "MyUserWidget.h"

UPROPERTY(EditDefaultsOnly, BlueprintReadOnly, Category = "UI")
TSubclassOf<UMyUserWidget> UserWidgetClass;
```

3. Set the widget class reference to your custom class in the constructor:

```cpp
YourCustomClass::YourCustomClass()
{
    // ...
    UserWidgetClass = UMyUserWidget::StaticClass(); // Use UMyUserWidget instead of UUserWidget
}
```

4. When you want to create and bind the widget:

```cpp
UMyUserWidget* CreatedWidget = CreateWidget<UMyUserWidget>(GetWorld(), UserWidgetClass);
if (CreatedWidget)
{
    // Now you can access the TextBlockWidget using the BindWidget syntax
    UTextBlock* TextBlock = CreatedWidget->TextBlockWidget;
    if (TextBlock)
    {
        TextBlock->SetText(FText::FromString(TEXT("Hello, BindWidget!")));
    }
    CreatedWidget->AddToViewport();
}
```

Please note that, to bind the widgets using the BindWidget meta keyword, you will have to create the UI layout and bind each widget component by hand in C++ using the UPROPERTY and GetWidgetFromName functions during the Initialize() function when the UUserWidget instance is created.

In summary, when using BindWidget with a C++-derived UUserWidget (UMyUserWidget in this example), you can access the bound widget components directly through code.
